result.execSummary:
The defendant Timothy C. Robinson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Timothy C. Robinson is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Timothy C. Robinson was found guilty of Failure to Support Child (120 Days+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.22(2).
  • Timothy C. Robinson was found guilty of Failure to Support Child (120 Days+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.22(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Case called at 11:16 AM.  Defendant Timothy C. Robinson in court with attorney Joanne M. Keane.  Katherine M. Findley appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Matter resolved.  Attorney Keane files plea and waiver of rights.  Defendant withdraws not guilty and enters plea of Guilty on Counts 1 and 2.  Court questions Defendant regarding Plea and Waiver.  Court also questions Attorney Keane regarding her client's plea/waiver of rights.  Sentence probation 3 years with conditions.  Court finds plea and waiver is made freely, knowingly, and intelligently.  Court accepts plea and finds Defendant Guilty on counts 1 and 2.  State moves for joint plea agreement.  Attorney Keane concurs with the State and makes statement on behalf of her client.  Defendant makes statement to Court.  The Court withheld sentence, ordered the Defendant be put on probation for a period of 3 years with conditions.
